ntional decision adopted in place of well-known alternatives during the Progressive Era, against past precedent and principle in several states.From efforts to convert expropriated Indigenous and Mexican land into common school funding in the 1850s, to reforms that directed state aid to expanding white suburbs during the years surrounding World War II, Dividing the Public traces, in intricate detail, how a host of policies connected to school funding have divided California by race and class over time. In bringing into view the neglected and poorly understood history of policymaking connected to school finance, Kelly offers a new story about the role public education played in shaping the racially segregated, economically divided, and politically fragmented world of the post-1945 metropolis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aDiscrimination & Race Relations. 4aU.S. HISTORY. 7aEDUCATION / Finance.2bisacsh  aeducation funding, financial inequality, local property tax, schooling resource disparities, tax in districts, educational policy, finance history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075184040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501773273zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501773273zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501773273/original  a978-3-11-075184-0 Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA